Introduction

Bitcoin is a cryptocurrency (virtual money) designed to act as a form of money and used to make payments outside the control of a group or entity. Therefore, it removes the need for third-party involvement such as banks and is not controlled by the government.

Being the first-ever cryptocurrency, it is an extremely volatile financial asset and has seen large fluctuations in price since its establishment in 2008.

Purpose of the Project

The purpose of this project is to:

✅ Analyse Bitcoin’s historical price and how its value has changed over time.
✅ Use Prophet forecasting to predict the future prices of Bitcoin.
✅ Identify seasonality patterns.

Prophet Model

In this section we identify trends and forecast the price of Bitcoin using Prophets forecasting tool.

The dataset used in this project was obtained from Kaggle. It contains the daily closing price of bitcoin. You can access the dataset here:
Bitcoin Historical Price Dataset (Kaggle)

Load Bitcoin Dataset

First, we load the dataset using read_csv.

#Load dataset
library(readr)
BTC_USD <- read_csv("data/BTC-USD.csv")

#Check dataset is loaded correctly
head(BTC_USD)

Formatting the Dataset

To use the Prophet Model we first must:

  • Convert the date column to Prophets date format (ds)
  • Set the price as the variable (y)
#Convert dataset to Prophet format
library(zoo)
BitcoinData <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(BTC_USD$Date), 
  y = BTC_USD$Price)

BitcoinData$ds <- as.Date(BitcoinData$ds)

Visualising Bitcoin Price

Before we forecast Bitcoins price, it would be a good idea to plot a chart of the historical price of Bitcoin.

For a clearer chart we use ggplot

#Plot Bitcoin Price History
plot(BitcoinData$ds, BitcoinData$y, 
     type = "l",
     main = "Bitcoin Price History",
     xlab = "Year", ylab = "Price (USD)")

Implement the Prophet Model

The Prophet model will first identify any trends or seasonality from the dataset.

#Check dataset for weekly and yearly seasonality
library(prophet)
BitcoinModel <- prophet(BitcoinData, 
                        yearly.seasonality = TRUE, 
                        weekly.seasonality = TRUE)

#Forecast next 365 days
FutureBitcoin <- make_future_dataframe(BitcoinModel, periods = 365, freq = "day")
BitcoinForecast <- predict(BitcoinModel, FutureBitcoin)

Forecasting Bitcoin Price

We can now plot the forecasted price of Bitcoin!

#Plot Bitcoin Forecasted model
plot(BitcoinModel, BitcoinForecast,
     main = "Bitcoin Price Forecast",
     xlab = "Year", ylab = "Price (USD)")

The plot shows the historical Bitcoin Price (black points) with the forecasted Bitcoin price (blue line). It also includes levels of uncertainty with the blue shaded area.

The forecast suggests a price will increase with a continuous upward trend

Seasonality

Prophet can also give us insights into weekly and yearly seasonality.

#Plots of Bitcoins seasonality
prophet_plot_components(BitcoinModel, BitcoinForecast)

From the weekly seasonality we can see that Monday has the highest increase in price whereas Tuesday has the highest decrease.

Futhermore, from the yearly seasonality we can see a large peak during January. We also see big price increases around June and December. On the other hand, April and October show the largest decreases in price for the year.
